<image 1> How does the green and photosynthesising mistletoe impact the tree it is hosting?

A. It will grow down into the roots and kill the tree.
B. Mistletoe is beneficial and increases the growth of the plant.
C. It just uses the tree for support and does not damage it.
D. I don't know and don't want to guess.
E. It has a very damaging impact on the health of the plant but localised to the place of infection.

The correct answer is:

E. It has a very damaging impact on the health of the plant but localised to the place of infection.

Mistletoe is a parasitic plant that attaches itself to the branches of a host tree and taps into its vascular system to extract nutrients and water. While mistletoe can photosynthesize, it still relies on the host tree for some of its nutritional needs. This parasitic relationship can weaken the host tree, especially if there is a large infestation. The damage is typically localized to the areas where the mistletoe is attached, but over time, it can stress the tree and potentially lead to its decline.
